															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/corerosion" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1033535); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1033535&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183391" alt="Corerosion" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1033535)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/corerosion" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1033535); return false;" >Corerosion</a></span> <span class="odate time_1330484547 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Feb 2012 03:02</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1384460">
									

<p>Mm I understand where you're coming from, I can see the convoluted descriptions being a detriment rather than a good thing. Still, I do wish to argue my stand:</p>
<p>The way I see it, the most important facet about this story I have written is the atmosphere of unease that I (hope) I managed to create, the sense to the reader that all is unwell. In part then, this is achieved through the graphic and long descriptions, the labored words mixing in with the disgusting sounds and imagery. The descriptions may not be entirely accurate, for example the one you pin-pointed about the spikes, but those are the closest I can come to describe the emotion in a manner I feel befitting it. When I feel a pain in my chest, it comes in sharp bursts, feeling as if something were puncturing me from the front, and each one sends a wave of emotion mixed with physical sensation to my head - thus, I used the phrase. Granted, not everyone may catch that, it is quite the personal description, but it feels right, placing it there.</p>
<p>On the other hand, as much as I hate to drop author names, (reminds me of Literature Class all over again), I can see supporting examples, and contradictory examples against this style of writing. For example, Roddy Doyle, who wrote a short horror story that I read recently, managed to give me a sense of unease with minimal description, mostly working through dialogue. It was simply &quot;He bit the head off the chicken&quot;. On the flip-side, we have Chuck Palahniuk, who writes certain stories in an intensely convoluted and graphic manner, using it to disgust and make the readers uncomfortable. I defy you to read Palahniuk's &quot;Guts&quot; and not feel queasy - (in fact it's famous for causing more than one person to throw up and even one to faint during a public reading).</p>
<p>Anyway, this style of writing is not for everyone, I understand, and well, I think I can see how my descriptions are flawed. If you read my other creepypasta story, <a href="/pitter-patter">Pitter=patter</a> (shameless promotion of it here), you'll see a much less labored descriptive style. I just felt that in this story, in this case, this form of description helped rather than hindered the tale. Thanks for the criticism and opinions, they caused me to think for a while.</p>

							</div>

								
					
