    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-1384528">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-1384528">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1384528)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1384528">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1313607"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1330492928 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Feb 2012 05:22</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1384528">
									

<p>Well, as Palahniuk said, himself, &quot;Until you can create something that captivates people, I'd invite you to just shut up.&quot; So who am I to judge? ;) You've certainly hit the right buttons, for some readers, which is a sign that you are doing something very right.</p>
<p>But I still think criticism has some value, as subjective as mine is, so I'm gonna reply&#8230;.</p>
<p>Pardon my blunt, but <em>Guts</em> doesn't quite work as a stylistic comparison, body horror aside. It's a hell of a lot better written, for one. The author's prose isn't laborious or sopping with adjectives; the sentences are almost staccato.</p>
<p>The criticism I was making is that you have too many damn modifiers. Everywhere. <em>Convoluted</em> can be effective; excess isn't the same thing. Let me try to illustrate by example: (<em>examples now behind a cut because yikes wall of text</em>)</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Her other hand shook as it edged towards the battered metal plate, slipped slightly in the pooling blood, and finally managed to clasp around the oozing organ, picking it up. It squelched in her grasp. Small showers of blood dripped from it, slipping from the cracks between her fingers and back into the plate, merging with the symphony of expectant silence in the operating room.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>VS: &quot;Her hand shook as it hesitated over the plate. The blood was slippery. She couldn't keep hold of the oozing thing without digging her fingers into it. It made a squelching sound, sickening loud in the silent room. She picked it up. Blood trickled down her wrist.&quot;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;the madness and darkness evaporated beneath the soothing touch of humanity, suffocated by the constricting knots of the straitjacket&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>VS: &quot;the darkness would evaporate beneath the touch of humanity, the madness choked in the knots of a straitjacket&quot;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;And here she was, holding a pillow above the face of some woman she didn’t know, pressing it down as hands clawed at her. The woman’s body, young and lithe except for the distended belly possessing her spawn, struggled and bucked under her grip, but she held on, a strength that could come only from insane hunger pressing down her arms. The monitor rattled on the table, unplugged cord scattering about the floor, the bed shivered with the dying woman’s convulsions. Her grip upon the pillow softened as the woman struggled less and less, until finally, the flailing hands fell limply against the sides of the bed.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>edit:</strong> now with more unsettling Biblical metaphor!<br />
VS: &quot;Here she was, pressing the pillow down as hands clawed at her. The stranger was young, her belly swollen like ripe fruit. The stranger's struggle was fierce, but hunger gave her inhuman strength. Hunger locked her arms and fingers until the knuckles whitened, even as the bed shuddered with convulsions. The distended belly quivered.</p>
<p>Then all was still.&quot;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>&#8230;.. Does using fewer words <em>really</em> take away from the mood or meaning of those passages?</p>

							</div>

								
