				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1313607"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1330510113 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Feb 2012 10:08</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1384627">
									

<p>Well, as far as laboriousness goes, <em>Guts</em> itself is overlong. Among other things.</p>
<p>(But I didn't find it particularly nauseating? Maybe familiarity with the instances of that particular injury makes a difference. &quot;Body horror&quot; probably just engages my curiosity and/or empathy more than it turns my stomach.)</p>
<p>It's worth pointing out that I find your concept more interesting than Palahniuk's. It could hit more emotions than just &quot;ew gross&quot; or &quot;woe is me I died while [EXPUNGED]&quot;, and the way you play with guilt, especially in the last lines, is a great example of that. The idea of breaking biologically-ingrained taboos&#8230;</p>
<p>I guess my point is: you could leave this as an (apparently effective) bit of creepypasta, or you could keep wrestling with it, and maybe get a neat little horror short story.</p>

							</div>

								
